summary:
The Security Council,
 Reaffirming previous resolutions on Timor-Leste, particularly resolution 1410 (2002),
 Supports the Special Representative of the Secretary-General and UNMISET,
 Welcomes progress in Timor-Leste with UNMISET's assistance,
 Notes ongoing security and stability challenges,
 Stresses improving the Timor-Leste police force is a key priority,
 Having considered the Secretary-General's special report (S/2003/243) and a letter from the Under-Secretary-General (S/2003/379),
1. Adjusts the police component of UNMISET to include: 
 (i) an internationally formed unit for one year; 
 (ii) additional training capacity; 
 (iii) greater emphasis on human rights and rule of law; 
 (iv) retention of a monitoring and advisory presence; 
 (v) follow-up on policing recommendations; 
 (vi) adjusted planning for policing authority transfer;
2. Adjusts the military component downsizing schedule, retaining two battalions and associated force elements until December 2003, with 1,750 military peacekeepers;
3. Requests a detailed military strategy by 20 May 2003;
4. Requests regular updates on implementation;
5. Urges the Government of Timor-Leste to work closely with UNMISET;
6. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
